# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azure-entra-id
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] In computer systems, an **access token** contains the security credentials for a login session and identifies the user, the user's groups, the user's privileges, and, in some cases, a particular application.*"RFC 6749 - The OAuth 2.0 Authorization Framework".
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] *RFC Editor*.* In some instances, one may be asked to enter an access token (e.g.
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] 40 random characters) rather than the usual password (it therefore should be kept secret just like a password).
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] An *access token* is an object encapsulating the security identity of a process or thread.
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] A token is used to make security decisions and to store tamper-proof information about some system entity.
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] While a token is generally used to represent only security information, it is capable of holding additional free-form data that can be attached while the token is being created.
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] Tokens can be duplicated without special privilege, for example to create a new token with lower levels of access rights to restrict the access of a launched application.
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] An access token is used by Windows when a process or thread tries to interact with objects that have security descriptors (*securable objects*).
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] In Windows, an access token is represented by the system object of type `Token`.
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] An access token is generated by the logon service when a user logs on to the system and the credentials provided by the user are authenticated against the authentication database.
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] The authentication database contains credential information required to construct the initial token for the logon session, including its user id, primary group id, all other groups it is part of, and other information.
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] The token is attached to the initial process created in the user session and inherited by subsequent processes created by the initial process.
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] Whenever such a process opens a handle to any resource which has access control enabled, Windows reconciles the data in the target object's security descriptor with the contents of the current effective access token.
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] The result of this access check evaluation is an indication of whether any access is allowed and, if so, what operations (read, write/modify, etc.) the calling application is allowed to perform.
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] Primary tokens can only be associated to processes, and they represent a process's security subject.
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] Processes initially inherit a copy of the parent process's primary token.
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] Impersonation is a security concept implemented in Windows NT that allows a server application to temporarily "be" the client in terms of access to secure objects.
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] , same as impersonation but extended to remote systems to which the server connects (through the preservation of credentials).
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] The client can choose the maximum impersonation level (if any) available to the server as a connection parameter.
[src:azure-entra-id/access-token] Impersonation tokens are usually created and associated to the current thread implicitly, by IPC mechanisms such as DCE RPC, DDE and named pipes.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] The terms "identity management" (IdM) and "identity and access management" are used interchangeably in the area of identity access management.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Identity-management systems, products, applications and platforms manage identifying and ancillary data about entities that include individuals, computer-related hardware, and software applications.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] IdM covers issues such as how users gain an identity, the roles, and sometimes the permissions that identity grants, the protection of that identity, and the technologies supporting that protection (e.g., network protocols, digital certificates, passwords, etc.).
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Identity management (IdM) is the task of controlling information about users on computers.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Such information includes information that authenticates the identity of a user, and information that describes data and actions they are authorized to access and/or perform.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] It also includes the management of descriptive information about the user and how and by whom that information can be accessed and modified.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] In addition to users, managed entities typically include hardware and network resources and even applications.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] The diagram below shows the relationship between the configuration and operation phases of IAM, as well as the distinction between identity management and access management.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Access control is the enforcement of access rights defined as part of access authorization.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Digital identity is an entity's online presence, encompassing personal identifying information (PII) and ancillary information.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] See OECD and NIST guidelines on protecting PII.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] It can be interpreted as the codification of identity names and attributes of a physical instance in a way that facilitates processing.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] A general model of identity can be constructed from a small set of axioms, for example that all identities in a given namespace are unique, or that such identities bear a specific relationship to corresponding entities in the real world.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Such an axiomatic model expresses "pure identity" in the sense that the model is not constrained by a specific application context.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] In general, an entity (real or virtual) can have multiple identities and each identity can encompass multiple attributes, some of which are unique within a given name space.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] The diagram below illustrates the conceptual relationship between identities and entities, as well as between identities and their attributes.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] In most theoretical and all practical models of digital identity, a given identity object consists of a finite set of properties (attribute values).
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] These properties record information about the object, either for purposes external to the model or to operate the model, for example in classification and retrieval.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] A "pure identity" model is strictly not concerned with the external semantics of these properties.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] The most common departure from "pure identity" in practice occurs with properties intended to assure some aspect of identity, for example a digital signature or software token which the model may use internally to verify some aspect of the identity in satisfaction of an external purpose.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] To the extent that the model expresses such semantics internally, it is not a pure model.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Contrast this situation with properties that might be externally used for purposes of information security such as managing access or entitlement, but which are simply stored, maintained and retrieved, without special treatment by the model.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] The absence of external semantics within the model qualifies it as a "pure identity" model.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Identity management can thus be defined as a set of operations on a given identity model, or more generally, as a set of capabilities with reference to it.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] In practice, identity management often expands to express how model content is to be provisioned and reconciled among multiple identity models.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] The process of reconciling accounts may also be referred to as de-provisioning.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] User access enables users to assume a specific digital identity across applications, which enables access controls to be assigned and evaluated against this identity.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] The use of a single identity for a given user across multiple systems eases tasks for administrators and users.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] It simplifies access monitoring and verification, and allows the organizations to minimize excessive privileges granted to one user.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Ensuring user access security is crucial in this process, as it involves protecting the integrity and confidentiality of user credentials and preventing unauthorized access.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Implementing robust authentication mechanisms, such as multi-factor authentication (MFA), regular security audits, and strict access controls, helps safeguard user identities and sensitive data.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] User access can be tracked from initiation to termination of user access.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] When organizations deploy an identity management process or system, their motivation is normally not primarily to manage a set of identities, but rather to grant appropriate access rights to those entities via their identities.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] In other words, access management is normally the motivation for identity management and the two sets of processes are consequently closely related.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Organizations continue to add services for both internal users and by customers.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Many such services require identity management to properly provide these services.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Increasingly, identity management has been partitioned from application functions so that a single identity can serve many or even all of an organization's activities.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] For internal use identity management is evolving to control access to all digital assets, including devices, network equipment, servers, portals, content, applications and/or products.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Services often require access to extensive information about a user, including address books, preferences, entitlements and contact information.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Since much of this information is subject to privacy and/or confidentiality requirements, controlling access to it is vital.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Identity federation comprises one or more systems that share user access and allow users to log in based on authenticating against one of the systems participating in the federation.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] This trust between several systems is often known as a "circle of trust".
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] In this setup, one system acts as the identity provider (IdP) and other systems act as service providers (SPs).
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] When a user needs to access some service controlled by SP, they first authenticate against the IdP.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Upon successful authentication, the IdP sends a secure "assertion" to the SP.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] "SAML assertions, specified using a markup language intended for describing security assertions, can be used by a verifier to make a statement to a relying party about the identity of a claimant.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] In addition to creation, deletion, modification of user identity data either assisted or self-service, identity management controls ancillary entity data for use by applications, such as contact information or location.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Putting personal information onto computer networks necessarily raises privacy concerns.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Absent proper protections, the data may be used to implement a surveillance society.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Social web and online social networking services make heavy use of identity management.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Helping users decide how to manage access to their personal information has become an issue of broad concern.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Research related to the management of identity covers disciplines such as technology, social sciences, humanities and the law.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Decentralized identity management is identity management based on decentralized identifiers (DIDs).
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Within the Seventh Research Framework Programme of the European Union from 2007 to 2013, several new projects related to Identity Management started.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] The PICOS Project investigates and develops a state-of-the-art platform for providing trust, privacy and identity management in mobile communities.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] SWIFT focuses on extending identity functions and federation to the network while addressing usability and privacy concerns and leverages identity technology as a key to integrate service and transport infrastructures for the benefit of users and the providers.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Ongoing projects include Future of Identity in the Information Society (FIDIS), GUIDE, and PRIME.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] In each organization there is normally a role or department that is responsible for managing the schema of digital identities of their staff and their own objects, which are represented by object identities or object identifiers (OID).
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] The organizational policies and processes and procedures related to the oversight of identity management are sometimes referred to as *Identity Governance and Administration* (IGA).
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] How effectively and appropriately such tools are used falls within scope of broader governance, risk management, and compliance regimes.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] An **identity-management system** refers to an information system, or to a set of technologies that can be used for enterprise or cross-network identity management.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] Identity and access management systems are central to meeting regulatory requirements across multiple sectors that mandate controls over who can access sensitive information.
[src:azure-entra-id/identity-management] NIST Special Publication 800-53 includes comprehensive identity and access management controls in the AC (Access Control) and IA (Identification and Authentication) control families, providing the reference framework for federal agency IAM implementations.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Usage of MFA has increased in recent years.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Security issues which can cause the bypass of MFA are fatigue attacks, phishing and SIM swapping.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Accounts with MFA enabled are significantly less likely to be compromised.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Authentication takes place when someone tries to log into a computer resource (such as a computer network, device, or application).
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] The resource requires the user to supply the identity by which the user is known to the resource, along with evidence of the authenticity of the user's claim to that identity.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Simple authentication requires only one such piece of evidence (factor), typically a password, or occasionally multiple pieces of evidence all of the same type, as with a credit card number and a card verification code (CVC).
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] For additional security, the resource may require more than one factor—multi-factor authentication, or two-factor authentication in cases where exactly two types of evidence are to be supplied.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] The use of multiple authentication factors to prove one's identity is based on the premise that an unauthorized actor is unlikely to be able to supply all of the factors required for access.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] If, in an authentication attempt, at least one of the components is missing or supplied incorrectly, the user's identity is not established with sufficient certainty and access to the asset (e.g., a building, or data) being protected by multi-factor authentication then remains blocked.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] An example of two-factor authentication is the withdrawing of money from an ATM; only the correct combination of a physically present bank card (something the user possesses) and a PIN (something the user knows) allows the transaction to be carried out.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Two other examples are to supplement a user-controlled password with a one-time password (OTP) or code generated or received by an authenticator (e.g. a security token or smartphone) that only the user possesses.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] An authenticator app enables two-factor authentication in a different way, by showing a randomly generated and constantly refreshing code, rather than sending an SMS or using another method.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] This code is a Time-based one-time password (a *TOTP*), and the authenticator app contains the key material that allows the generation of these codes.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Knowledge factors ("something only the user knows") are a form of authentication.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] In this form, the user is required to prove knowledge of a secret in order to authenticate.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] A password is a secret word or string of characters that is used for user authentication.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] This is the most commonly used mechanism of authentication.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Many multi-factor authentication techniques rely on passwords as one factor of authentication.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Variations include both longer ones formed from multiple words (a passphrase) and the shorter, purely numeric, PIN commonly used for ATM access.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Traditionally, passwords are expected to be memorized, but can also be written down on a hidden paper or text file.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Possession factors ("something only the user has") have been used for authentication for centuries, in the form of a key to a lock.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] The basic principle is that the key embodies a secret that is shared between the lock and the key, and the same principle underlies possession factor authentication in computer systems.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] A security token is an example of a possession factor.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] *soft token*) is a type of two-factor authentication security device that may be used to authorize the use of computer services.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] A soft token may not be a device the user interacts with.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Typically an X.509v3 certificate is loaded onto the device and stored securely to serve this purpose.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Inherent factors ("something the user is"), are factors associated with the user, and are usually biometric methods, including fingerprint, face, voice, or iris recognition.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Behavioral biometrics such as keystroke dynamics can also be used.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Increasingly, a fourth factor is coming into play involving the physical location of the user.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] While hard wired to the corporate network, a user could be allowed to login using only a pin code, whereas if the user was working remotely, a more secure MFA method such as entering a code from a soft token as well could be required.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Adapting the type of MFA method and frequency to a users' location will enable the avoidance of risks common to remote working.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Systems for network admission control work in similar ways where the level of network access can be contingent on the specific network a device is connected to, such as Wi-Fi vs wired connectivity.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] This also allows a user to move between offices and dynamically receive the same level of network access in each.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Two-factor authentication over text message was developed as early as 1996, when AT&T described a system for authorizing transactions based on an exchange of codes over two-way pagers.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Many multi-factor authentication vendors offer mobile phone-based authentication.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Some methods include push-based authentication, QR code-based authentication, one-time password authentication (event-based and time-based), and SMS-based verification.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] SMS-based verification suffers from some security concerns.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Phones can be cloned, apps can run on several phones and cell-phone maintenance personnel can read SMS texts.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Not least, cell phones can be compromised in general, meaning the phone is no longer something only the user has.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] The major drawback of authentication including something the user possesses is that the user must carry around the physical token (the USB stick, the bank card, the key or similar), practically at all times.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Many organizations forbid carrying USB and electronic devices in or out of premises owing to malware and data theft risks, and most important machines do not have USB ports for the same reason.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Physical tokens usually do not scale, typically requiring a new token for each new account and system.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Procuring and subsequently replacing tokens of this kind involves costs.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] In addition, there are inherent conflicts and unavoidable trade-offs between usability and security.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Two-step authentication involving mobile phones and smartphones provides an alternative to dedicated physical devices.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] To authenticate, people can use their personal access codes to the device (i.e. something that only the individual user knows) plus a one-time-valid, dynamic passcode, typically consisting of 4 to 6 digits.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] The passcode can be sent to their mobile device by SMS or can be generated by a one-time passcode-generator app.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] In both cases, the advantage of using a mobile phone is that there is no need for an additional dedicated token, as users tend to carry their mobile devices around at all times.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Notwithstanding the popularity of SMS verification, security advocates have publicly criticized SMS verification, and in July 2016, a United States NIST draft guideline proposed deprecating it as a form of authentication.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] A year later NIST reinstated SMS verification as a valid authentication channel in the finalized guideline.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] As early as 2011, Duo Security was offering push notifications for MFA via a mobile app.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] In 2016 and 2017 respectively, both Google and Apple started offering user two-step authentication with push notifications as an alternative method.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Security of SMS-delivered security tokens fully depends on the mobile operator's operational security and can be easily breached by wiretapping or SIM cloning by national security agencies.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] The Payment Card Industry (PCI) Data Security Standard, requirement 8.3, requires the use of MFA for all remote network access that originates from outside the network to a Card Data Environment (CDE).
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Beginning with PCI-DSS version 3.2, the use of MFA is required for all administrative access to the CDE, even if the user is within a trusted network.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] The second Payment Services Directive requires "strong customer authentication" on most electronic payments in the European Economic Area since September 14, 2019.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] In India, the Reserve Bank of India mandated two-factor authentication for all online transactions made using a debit or credit card using either a password or a one-time password sent over SMS.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] This requirement was removed in 2016 for transactions up to ₹2,000 after opting-in with the issuing bank.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Vendors such as Uber have been mandated by the bank to amend their payment processing systems in compliance with this two-factor authentication rollout.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Details for authentication for federal employees and contractors in the U.S. are defined in Homeland Security Presidential Directive 12 (HSPD-12).
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] IT regulatory standards for access to federal government systems require the use of multi-factor authentication to access sensitive IT resources, for example when logging on to network devices to perform administrative tasks and when accessing any computer using a privileged login.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] NIST Special Publication 800-63-3 discusses various forms of two-factor authentication and provides guidance on using them in business processes requiring different levels of assurance.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] In response to the publication, numerous authentication vendors began improperly promoting challenge-questions, secret images, and other knowledge-based methods as "multi-factor" authentication.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Considering the reliability of the method, in some countries, MFA is obligatory in certain industries, such as healthcare, to prevent the theft of sensitive information.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] In the healthcare sector, the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) Security Rule has historically listed access controls as a required implementation specification but did not explicitly mandate multi-factor authentication.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] The HHS Office for Civil Rights noted in enforcement guidance that the lack of MFA was a contributing factor in multiple healthcare data breaches investigated under HIPAA.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] In December 2024, HHS published a Notice of Proposed Rulemaking that would make multi-factor authentication a mandatory requirement for all HIPAA-regulated entities accessing electronic protected health information.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] According to proponents, multi-factor authentication could drastically reduce the incidence of online identity theft and other online fraud, because the victim's password would no longer be enough to give a thief permanent access to their information.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] However, many multi-factor authentication approaches remain vulnerable to phishing, man-in-the-browser, and man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] To counter phishing attacks, users should not share their verification codes with anyone, and many web application providers will place an advisory in an e-mail or SMS containing a code.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] In May 2017, O2 Telefónica, a German mobile service provider, confirmed that cybercriminals had exploited SS7 vulnerabilities to bypass SMS based two-step authentication to do unauthorized withdrawals from users' bank accounts.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] The criminals first infected the account holder's computers in an attempt to steal their bank account credentials and phone numbers.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Then the attackers purchased access to a fake telecom provider and set up a redirect for the victim's phone number to a handset controlled by them.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Finally, the attackers logged into victims' online bank accounts and requested for the money on the accounts to be withdrawn to accounts owned by the criminals.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] SMS passcodes were routed to phone numbers controlled by the attackers and the criminals transferred the money out.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] An increasingly common approach to defeating MFA is to bombard the user with many requests to accept a log-in, until the user eventually succumbs to the volume of requests and by mistake accepts one.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] This form of social engineering is called *multi-factor authentication fatigue attack* (also MFA fatigue attack or MFA bombing), and may include other elements, such as calls pretending to be from IT support.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] When MFA applications are configured to send push notifications to end users, an attacker can send a flood of login attempts in the hope that a user will click on accept at least once.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] In 2022, Microsoft deployed a mitigation against MFA fatigue attacks with their authenticator app, by optionally requiring the user to type in a number in addition to clicking "approve".
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] In September 2022 Uber security was breached by a member of Lapsus$ using a multi-factor fatigue attack.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] In early 2024, a small percentage of Apple consumers experienced a MFA fatigue attack that was caused by a hacker that bypassed the rate limit and Captcha on Apple’s “Forgot Password” page.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Many multi-factor authentication products require users to deploy client software to make multi-factor authentication systems work.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Some vendors have created separate installation packages for network login, Web access credentials, and VPN connection credentials.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] For such products, there may be four or five different software packages to push down to the client PC in order to make use of the token or smart card.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] This translates to four or five packages on which version control has to be performed, and four or five packages to check for conflicts with business applications.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] If access can be operated using web pages, it is possible to limit the overheads outlined above to a single application.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] With other multi-factor authentication technology such as hardware token products, no software must be installed by end-users.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Some studies have shown that poorly implemented MFA recovery procedures can introduce new vulnerabilities that attackers may exploit.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] There are drawbacks to multi-factor authentication that are keeping many approaches from becoming widespread.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Some users have difficulty keeping track of a hardware token or USB plug.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Many users do not have the technical skills needed to install a client-side software certificate by themselves.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Generally, multi-factor solutions require additional investment for implementation and costs for maintenance.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Most hardware token-based systems are proprietary, and some vendors charge an annual fee per user.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Deployment of hardware tokens is logistically challenging.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Hardware tokens may get damaged or lost, and issuance of tokens in large industries such as banking or even within large enterprises needs to be managed.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] In addition to deployment costs, multi-factor authentication often carries significant additional support costs.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] A 2008 survey of over 120 U.S. credit unions by the *Credit Union Journal* reported on the support costs associated with two-factor authentication.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] In their report, software certificates and software toolbar approaches were reported to have the highest support costs.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] Research into deployments of multi-factor authentication schemes has shown that one of the elements that tend to impact the adoption of such systems is the line of business of the organization that deploys the multi-factor authentication system.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] While the perception is that multi-factor authentication is within the realm of perfect security, Roger Grimes writes that if not properly implemented and configured, multi-factor authentication can in fact be easily defeated.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] In 2013, Kim Dotcom claimed to have invented two-factor authentication in a 2000 patent, and briefly threatened to sue all the major web services.
[src:azure-entra-id/multi-factor-authentication] However, the European Patent Office revoked his patent in light of an earlier 1998 U.S. patent held by AT&T.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Generally, the OAuth protocol provides a way for resource owners to provide a client application with secure delegated access to server resources.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] It specifies a process for resource owners to authorize third-party access to their server resources without providing credentials.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Designed specifically to work with Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP), OAuth essentially allows access tokens to be issued to third-party clients by an authorization server, with the approval of the resource owner.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] The third party then uses the access token to access the protected resources hosted by the resource server.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] OAuth began in November 2006 when Blaine Cook was developing an OpenID implementation for Twitter.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Meanwhile, Ma.gnolia needed a solution to allow its members with OpenIDs to authorize Mac OS X Dashboard widgets to access their service.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Cook, Chris Messina and Larry Halff from Magnolia met with David Recordon to discuss using OpenID with the Twitter and Magnolia APIs to delegate authentication.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] They concluded that there were no open standards for API access delegation.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] The OAuth discussion group was created in April 2007, for a small group of implementers to write the draft proposal for an open protocol.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] DeWitt Clinton from Google learned of the OAuth project, and expressed his interest in supporting the effort.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] In July 2007, the team drafted an initial specification.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Eran Hammer joined and coordinated the many OAuth contributions creating a more formal specification.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] On 3 October 2007, the OAuth Core 1.0 final draft was released.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] At the 73rd Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) meeting in Minneapolis in November 2008, an OAuth BoF was held to discuss bringing the protocol into the IETF for further standardization work.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] The event was well attended and there was wide support for formally chartering an OAuth working group within the IETF.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] The OAuth 1.0 protocol was published as RFC 5849, an informational Request for Comments, in April 2010.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Since 31 August 2010, all third party Twitter applications have been required to use OAuth.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] The OAuth 2.0 framework was published considering additional use cases and extensibility requirements gathered from the wider IETF community.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Albeit being built on the OAuth 1.0 deployment experience, OAuth 2.0 is not backwards compatible with OAuth 1.0.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] OAuth 2.0 was published as RFC 6749 and the Bearer Token Usage specification as RFC 6750, both standards track Requests for Comments, in October 2012.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] As of November 2024, the OAuth 2.1 Authorization Framework draft is a work in progress.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] It consolidates the functionality in RFCs OAuth 2.0, OAuth 2.0 for Native Apps, Proof Key for Code Exchange, OAuth 2.0 for Browser-Based Apps, OAuth Security Best Current, and Bearer Token Usage.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] On 23 April 2009, a session fixation security flaw in the 1.0 protocol was announced.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] It affects the OAuth authorization flow (also known as "3-legged OAuth") in OAuth Core 1.0 Section 6.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Version 1.0a of the OAuth Core protocol was issued to address this issue.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] In January 2013, the Internet Engineering Task Force published a threat model for OAuth 2.0.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Among the threats outlined is one called "Open Redirector"; in early 2014, a variant of this was described under the name "Covert Redirect" by Wang Jing.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] OAuth 2.0 has been analyzed using formal web protocol analysis.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] This analysis revealed that in setups with multiple authorization servers, one of which is behaving maliciously, clients can become confused about the authorization server to use and may forward secrets to the malicious authorization server (AS Mix-Up Attack).
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] This prompted the creation of a new best current practice internet draft that sets out to define a new security standard for OAuth 2.0.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Assuming a fix against the AS Mix-Up Attack in place, the security of OAuth 2.0 has been proven under strong attacker models using formal analysis.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] One implementation of OAuth 2.0 with numerous security flaws has been exposed.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] In April and May 2017, about one million users of Gmail (less than 0.1% of users as of May 2017) were targeted by an OAuth-based phishing attack, receiving an email purporting to be from a colleague, employer or friend wanting to share a document on Google Docs.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Those who clicked on the link within the email were directed to sign in and allow a potentially malicious third-party program called "Google Apps" to access their "email account, contacts and online documents".
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Within "approximately one hour", the phishing attack was stopped by Google, who advised those who had given "Google Apps" access to their email to revoke such access and change their passwords.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] In the draft of OAuth 2.1 the use of the PKCE (RFC 7636) extension for native apps has been recommended to all kinds of OAuth clients, including web applications and other confidential clients in order to prevent malicious browser extensions from performing OAuth 2.0 code injection attacks.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] OAuth framework specifies several grant types for different use cases.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Facebook's Graph API only supports OAuth 2.0.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Google supports OAuth 2.0 as the recommended authorization mechanism for all of its APIs.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Microsoft also supports OAuth 2.0 for various APIs and its Azure Active Directory service, which is used to secure many Microsoft and third party APIs.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] OAuth can be used as an authorizing mechanism to access secured RSS/Atom feeds.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Access to RSS/ATOM feeds that require authentication has always been an issue.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] For example, an RSS feed from a secured Google Site could not have been accessed using Google Reader.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Instead, three-legged OAuth would have been used to authorize that RSS client to access the feed from the Google Site.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Free software client implementations of the OAuth2 protocol such as the LibreOffice OAuth2OOo extension allows access to remote resources (ie: via the Google API or the Microsoft Graph API and OAuth 2.0) and possibly even with the LibreOffice Basic language.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] This makes it very easy to write and use HTTP requests supporting the OAuth 2.0 protocol in LibreOffice macros.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] OAuth is a service that is complementary to and distinct from OpenID.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] OAuth is unrelated to OATH, which is a reference architecture for authentication, not a standard for authorization.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] However, OAuth is directly related to OpenID Connect (OIDC), since OIDC is an authentication layer built on top of OAuth 2.0.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] OAuth is also unrelated to XACML, which is an authorization policy standard.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] OAuth can be used in conjunction with XACML, where OAuth is used for ownership consent and access delegation whereas XACML is used to define the authorization policies (e.g., managers can view documents in their region).
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] OAuth is an *authorization* protocol, rather than an *authentication* protocol.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Using OAuth on its own as an authentication method may be referred to as pseudo-authentication.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] The following diagrams highlight the differences between using OpenID (specifically designed as an authentication protocol) and OAuth for authorization.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] The site sees that the user is not authenticated.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] It formulates a request for the identity provider, encodes it, and sends it to the user as part of a redirect URL.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Once the identity provider is satisfied that the user is sufficiently authenticated, it processes the application's request, formulates a response, and sends that back to the user along with a redirect URL back to the application.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] The application decodes the identity provider's response, and carries on accordingly.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] (OAuth only) The response includes an access token which the application can use to gain direct access to the identity provider's services on the user's behalf.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] The access token acts as a kind of "valet key" that the application can include with its requests to the identity provider, which prove that it has permission from the user to access those APIs.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Because the identity provider typically (but not always) authenticates the user as part of the process of granting an OAuth access token, it is tempting to view a successful OAuth access token request as an authentication method itself.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] However, because OAuth was not designed with this use case in mind, making this assumption can lead to major security flaws.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] XACML is a policy-based, attribute-based access control authorization framework.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] XACML and OAuth can be combined to deliver a more comprehensive approach to authorization.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] OAuth does not provide a policy language with which to define access control policies.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] XACML can be used for its policy language.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Where OAuth focuses on delegated access (I, the user, grant Twitter access to my Facebook wall), and identity-centric authorization, XACML takes an attribute-based approach which can consider attributes of the user, the action, the resource, and the context (who, what, where, when, how).
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] XACML provides more fine-grained access control than OAuth does.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] OAuth is limited in granularity to the coarse functionality (the scopes) exposed by the target service.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] As a result, it often makes sense to combine OAuth and XACML together where OAuth will provide the delegated access use case and consent management and XACML will provide the authorization policies that work on the applications, processes, and data.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Lastly, XACML can work transparently across multiple stacks (APIs, web SSO, ESBs, home-grown apps, databases...).
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] OAuth focuses exclusively on HTTP-based apps.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Eran Hammer resigned from his role of lead author for the OAuth 2.0 project, withdrew from the IETF working group, and removed his name from the specification in July 2012.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Hammer cited a conflict between web and enterprise cultures as his reason for leaving, noting that IETF is a community that is "all about enterprise use cases" and "not capable of simple".
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] "What is now offered is a blueprint for an authorization protocol", he noted, "that is the enterprise way", providing a "whole new frontier to sell consulting services and integration solutions".
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] In comparing OAuth 2.0 with OAuth 1.0, Hammer points out that it has become "more complex, less interoperable, less useful, more incomplete, and most importantly, less secure".
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] He explains how architectural changes for 2.0 unbound tokens from clients, removed all signatures and cryptography at a protocol level and added expiring tokens (because tokens could not be revoked) while complicating the processing of authorization.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] David Recordon later also removed his name from the specifications for unspecified reasons.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] Dick Hardt took over the editor role, and the framework was published in October 2012.
[src:azure-entra-id/oauth] David Harris, author of the email client Pegasus Mail, has criticised OAuth 2.0 as "an absolute dog's breakfast", requiring developers to write custom modules specific to each service (Gmail, Microsoft Mail services, etc.), and to register specifically with them.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The OpenID standard provides a framework for the communication that must take place between the identity provider and the OpenID acceptor (the "relying party").
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] An extension to the standard (the OpenID Attribute Exchange) facilitates the transfer of user attributes, such as name and gender, from the OpenID identity provider to the relying party (each relying party may request a different set of attributes, depending on its requirements).
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The OpenID protocol does not rely on a central authority to authenticate a user's identity.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Moreover, neither services nor the OpenID standard may mandate a specific means by which to authenticate users, allowing for approaches ranging from the common (such as passwords) to the novel (such as smart cards or biometrics).
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The final version of OpenID is OpenID 2.0, finalized and published in December 2007.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The term *OpenID* may also refer to an identifier as specified in the OpenID standard; these identifiers take the form of a unique Uniform Resource Identifier (URI), and are managed by some "OpenID provider" that handles authentication.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Facebook did use OpenID in the past, but moved to Facebook Connect.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Blogger also used OpenID, but since May 2018 no longer supports it.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] OpenID is a decentralized authentication protocol that allows users to authenticate with multiple websites using a single set of credentials, eliminating the need for separate usernames and passwords for each website.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] OpenID authenticates a user with an identity provider (IdP), who then provides the user with a unique identifier (called an OpenID).
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] This identifier can then be used to authenticate the user with any website that supports OpenID.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] When a user visits a website that supports OpenID authentication, the website will redirect the user to their chosen IdP.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The IdP will then prompt the user to authenticate themselves (e.g., by entering a username and password).
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Once the user is authenticated, the IdP will generate an OpenID and send it back to the website.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The website can then use this OpenID to authenticate the user without needing to know their actual credentials.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] OpenID is built on top of several existing standards, including HTTP, HTML, and XML.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] OpenID relies on a number of technologies, including a discovery mechanism that allows websites to find the IdP associated with a particular OpenID, as well as security mechanisms to protect against phishing and other attacks.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] One of the key benefits of OpenID is that it allows users to control their own identity information, rather than relying on individual websites to store and manage their login credentials.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] This can be particularly important in cases where websites are vulnerable to security breaches or where users are concerned about the privacy of their personal information.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] OpenID has been widely adopted by a number of large websites and service providers, including Google, Yahoo!, and PayPal.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The protocol is also used by a number of open source projects and frameworks, including Ruby on Rails and Django.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The end user interacts with a relying party (such as a website) that provides an option to specify an OpenID for the purposes of authentication; an end user typically has previously registered an OpenID (e.g.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] `alice.openid.example.org`) with an OpenID provider (e.g.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The relying party typically transforms the OpenID into a canonical URL form (e.g.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The `checkid_immediate` mode can fall back to the `checkid_setup` mode if the operation cannot be automated.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] First, the relying party and the OpenID provider (optionally) establish a shared secret, referenced by an *associate handle*, which the relying party then stores.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] If using the `checkid_setup` mode, the relying party redirects the end user's user-agent to the OpenID provider so the end user can authenticate directly with the OpenID provider.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The method of authentication may vary, but typically, an OpenID provider prompts the end user for a password or some cryptographic token, and then asks whether the end user trusts the relying party to receive the necessary identity details.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] If the end user declines the OpenID provider's request to trust the relying party, then the user-agent is redirected back to the relying party with a message indicating that authentication was rejected; the relying party in turn refuses to authenticate the end user.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] If the end user accepts the OpenID provider's request to trust the relying party, then the user-agent is redirected back to the relying party along with the end user's credentials.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] That relying party must then confirm that the credentials really came from the OpenID provider.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In contrast, a *stateless* or *dumb* relying party must make one more background request (`check_authentication`) to ensure that the data indeed came from the OpenID provider.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] After the OpenID has been verified, authentication is considered successful and the end user is considered logged into the relying party under the identity specified by the given OpenID (e.g.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The relying party typically then stores the end user's OpenID along with the end user's other session information.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] To obtain an OpenID-enabled URL that can be used to log into OpenID-enabled websites, a user registers an OpenID identifier with an identity provider.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Identity providers offer the ability to register a URL (typically a third-level domain, e.g. username.example.com) that will automatically be configured with OpenID authentication service.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Once they have registered an OpenID, a user can also use an existing URL under their own control (such as a blog or home page) as an alias or "delegated identity".
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] They simply insert the appropriate OpenID tags in the HTML or serve a Yadis document.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Starting with OpenID Authentication 2.0 (and some 1.1 implementations), there are two types of identifiers that can be used with OpenID: URLs and XRIs.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] XRIs are a new form of Internet identifier designed specifically for cross-domain digital identity.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] For example, XRIs come in two forms—i-names and i-numbers—that are usually registered simultaneously as synonyms.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] I-names are reassignable (like domain names), while i-numbers are never reassigned.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] When an XRI i-name is used as an OpenID identifier, it is immediately resolved to the synonymous i-number (the CanonicalID element of the XRDS document).
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] This i-number is the OpenID identifier stored by the relying party.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In this way, both the user and the relying party are protected from the end user's OpenID identity ever being taken over by another party as can happen with a URL based on a reassignable DNS name.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The OpenID Foundation (OIDF) promotes and enhances the OpenID community and technologies.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The OIDF is a non-profit international standards development organization of individual developers, government agencies and companies who wish to promote and protect OpenID.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The OpenID Foundation was formed in June 2007 and serves as a public trust organization representing an open community of developers, vendors and users.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] OIDF assists the community by providing needed infrastructure and help in promoting and supporting adoption of OpenID.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] This includes managing intellectual property and trade marks as well a fostering viral growth and global participation in OpenID.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] OIDF is a global organization to promote digital identity and to encourage the further adoption of OpenID, the OIDF has encouraged the creation of member chapters.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Member chapters are officially part of the Foundation and work within their own constituency to support the development and adoption of OpenID as a framework for user-centric identity on the internet.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The OIDF ensures that OpenID specifications are freely implementable therefore the OIDF requires all contributors to sign a contribution agreement.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] This agreement both grants a copyright license to the Foundation to publish the collective specifications and includes a patent non-assertion agreement.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The non-assertion agreement states that the contributor will not sue someone for implementing OpenID specifications.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The OpenID trademark in the United States was assigned to the OpenID Foundation in March 2008.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] It had been registered by NetMesh Inc. before the OpenID Foundation was operational.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In Europe, as of August 31, 2007, the OpenID trademark is registered to the OpenID Europe Foundation.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The OpenID logo was designed by Randy "ydnar" Reddig, who in 2005 had expressed plans to transfer the rights to an OpenID organization.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Sun Microsystems, VeriSign and a number of smaller companies involved in OpenID have issued patent non-assertion covenants covering OpenID 1.1 specifications.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The covenants state that the companies will not assert any of their patents against OpenID implementations and will revoke their promises from anyone who threatens, or asserts, patents against OpenID implementors.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In March, 2012, a research paper reported two generic security issues in OpenID.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Both issues allow an attacker to sign in to a victim's relying party accounts.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] For the first issue, OpenID and Google (an Identity Provider of OpenID) both published security advisories to address it.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Google's advisory says "An attacker could forge an OpenID request that doesn't ask for the user's email address, and then insert an unsigned email address into the IdPs response.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] If the attacker relays this response to a website that doesn't notice that this attribute is unsigned, the website may be tricked into logging the attacker in to any local account." The research paper claims that many popular websites have been confirmed vulnerable, including Yahoo!
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Mail, smartsheet.com, Zoho, manymoon.com, diigo.com.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The researchers have notified the affected parties, who have then fixed their vulnerable code.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] For the second issue, the paper called it "Data Type Confusion Logic Flaw", which also allows attackers to sign in to victims' RP accounts.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Google and PayPal were initially confirmed vulnerable.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] OpenID published a vulnerability report on the flaw.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The report says Google and PayPal have applied fixes, and suggest other OpenID vendors to check their implementations.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Some observers have suggested that OpenID has security weaknesses and may prove vulnerable to phishing attacks.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] For example, a malicious relaying party may forward the end user to a bogus identity provider authentication page asking that end user to input their credentials.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] On completion of this, the malicious party (who in this case also controls the bogus authentication page) could then have access to the end user's account with the identity provider, and then use that end user's OpenID to log into other services.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In an attempt to combat possible phishing attacks, some OpenID providers mandate that the end user needs to be authenticated with them prior to an attempt to authenticate with the relying party.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] This relies on the end user knowing the policy of the identity provider.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Other security issues identified with OpenID involve lack of privacy and failure to address the trust problem.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] However, this problem is not unique to OpenID and is simply the state of the Internet as commonly used.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The Identity Provider does, however, get a log of your OpenID logins; they know when you logged into what website, making cross-site tracking much easier.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] A compromised OpenID account is also likely to be a more serious breach of privacy than a compromised account on a single site.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Another important vulnerability is present in the last step in the authentication scheme when TLS/SSL are not used: the redirect-URL from the identity provider to the relying party.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The problem with this redirect is the fact that anyone who can obtain this URL (e.g. by sniffing the wire) can replay it and get logged into the site as the victim user.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Some of the identity providers use nonces (a number used just once) to allow a user to log into the site once and fail all the consecutive attempts.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The nonce solution works if the user is the first one to use the URL.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] However, a fast attacker who is sniffing the wire can obtain the URL and immediately reset a user's TCP connection (as an attacker is sniffing the wire and knows the required TCP sequence numbers) and then execute the replay attack as described above.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Thus nonces only protect against passive attackers, but cannot prevent active attackers from executing the replay attack.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Use of TLS/SSL in the authentication process can significantly reduce this risk.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] On May 1, 2014, a bug dubbed "Covert Redirect related to OAuth 2.0 and OpenID" was disclosed.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] It was discovered by mathematics doctoral student Wang Jing at the School of Physical and Mathematical Sciences, Nanyang Technological University, Singapore.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The announcement of OpenID is: "'Covert Redirect', publicized in May 2014, is an instance of attackers using open redirectors – a well-known threat, with well-known means of prevention.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] "The general consensus, so far, is that Covert Redirect is not as bad, but still a threat.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] A patch was not immediately made available.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Ori Eisen, founder, chairman and chief innovation officer at 41st Parameter told Sue Marquette Poremba, "In any distributed system, we are counting of the good nature of the participants to do the right thing.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In cases like OAuth and OpenID, the distribution is so vast that it is unreasonable to expect each and every website to patch up in the near future".
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The original OpenID authentication protocol was developed in May 2005 by Brad Fitzpatrick, creator of popular community website LiveJournal, while working at Six Apart.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Initially referred to as Yadis (an acronym for "Yet another distributed identity system"), it was named OpenID after the openid.net domain name was given to Six Apart to use for the project.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] OpenID support was soon implemented on LiveJournal and fellow LiveJournal engine community DeadJournal for blog post comments and quickly gained attention in the digital identity community.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Web developer JanRain was an early supporter of OpenID, providing OpenID software libraries and expanding its business around OpenID-based services.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In late June, discussions started between OpenID users and developers from enterprise software company NetMesh, leading to collaboration on interoperability between OpenID and NetMesh's similar Light-weight Identity (LID) protocol.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The direct result of the collaboration was the Yadis discovery protocol, adopting the name originally used for OpenID.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The new Yadis was announced on October 24, 2005.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] After a discussion at the 2005 Internet Identity Workshop a few days later, XRI/i-names developers joined the Yadis project, contributing their Extensible Resource Descriptor Sequence (XRDS) format for utilization in the protocol.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In December, developers at Sxip Identity began discussions with the OpenID/Yadis community after announcing a shift in the development of version 2.0 of its Simple Extensible Identity Protocol (SXIP) to URL-based identities like LID and OpenID.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In March 2006, JanRain developed a Simple Registration (SREG) extension for OpenID enabling primitive profile-exchange and in April submitted a proposal to formalize extensions to OpenID.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The same month, work had also begun on incorporating full XRI support into OpenID.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Around early May, key OpenID developer David Recordon left Six Apart, joining VeriSign to focus more on digital identity and guidance for the OpenID spec.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] By early June, the major differences between the SXIP 2.0 and OpenID projects were resolved with the agreement to support multiple personas in OpenID by submission of an identity provider URL rather than a full identity URL.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Late in 2006, a ZDNet opinion piece made the case for OpenID to users, web site operators and entrepreneurs.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] On January 31, 2007, Symantec announced support for OpenID in its Identity Initiative products and services.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] A week later, on February 6 Microsoft made a joint announcement with JanRain, Sxip, and VeriSign to collaborate on interoperability between OpenID and Microsoft's Windows CardSpace digital identity platform, with particular focus on developing a phishing-resistant authentication solution for OpenID.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] As part of the collaboration, Microsoft pledged to support OpenID in its future identity server products and JanRain, Sxip, and VeriSign pledged to add support for Microsoft's Information Card profile to their future identity solutions.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In mid-February, AOL announced that an experimental OpenID provider service was functional for all AOL and AOL Instant Messenger (AIM) accounts.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In May, Sun Microsystems began working with the OpenID community, announcing an OpenID program, as well as entering a non-assertion covenant with the OpenID community, pledging not to assert any of its patents against implementations of OpenID.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In June, OpenID leadership formed the OpenID Foundation, an Oregon-based public benefit corporation for managing the OpenID brand and property.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The same month, an independent OpenID Europe Foundation was formed in Belgium by Snorri Giorgetti.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] By early December, non-assertion agreements were collected by the major contributors to the protocol and the final OpenID Authentication 2.0 and OpenID Attribute Exchange 1.0 specifications were ratified on December 5.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In mid-January 2008, Yahoo! announced initial OpenID 2.0 support, both as a provider and as a relying party, releasing the provider service by the end of the month.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In early February, Google, IBM, Microsoft, VeriSign and Yahoo! joined the OpenID Foundation as corporate board members.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Around early May, SourceForge, Inc. introduced OpenID provider and relying party support to leading open source software development website SourceForge.net.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In late July, popular social network service MySpace announced support for OpenID as a provider.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In late October, Google launched support as an OpenID provider and Microsoft announced that Windows Live ID would support OpenID.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In November, JanRain announced a free hosted service, RPX Basic, that allows websites to begin accepting OpenIDs for registration and login without having to install, integrate and configure the OpenID open source libraries.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In January 2009, PayPal joined the OpenID Foundation as a corporate member, followed shortly by Facebook in February.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The OpenID Foundation formed an executive committee and appointed Don Thibeau as executive director.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In March, MySpace launched their previously announced OpenID provider service, enabling all MySpace users to use their MySpace URL as an OpenID.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In May, Facebook launched their relying party functionality, letting users use an automatic login-enabled OpenID account (e.g.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In September 2013, Janrain announced that MyOpenID.com would be shut down on February 1, 2014; a pie chart showed Facebook and Google dominate the social login space as of Q2 2013.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Facebook has since left OpenID; it is no longer a sponsor, represented on the board, or permitting OpenID logins.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In May 2016, Symantec announced that they would be discontinuing their pip.verisignlabs.com OpenID personal identity portal service.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In March 2018, Stack Overflow announced an end to OpenID support, citing insufficient usage to justify the cost.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In the announcement, it was stated that based on activity, users strongly preferred Facebook, Google, and e-mail/password based account authentication.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] OpenID is a way to use a single set of user credentials to access multiple sites, while OAuth facilitates the authorization of one site to access and use information related to the user's account on another site.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Although OAuth is not an authentication protocol, it can be used as part of one.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The following drawing highlights the differences between using OpenID versus OAuth for authentication.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Note that with OpenID, the process starts with the application asking the user for their identity (typically an OpenID URI), whereas in the case of OAuth, the application directly requests a limited access OAuth Token (valet key) to access the APIs (enter the house) on user's behalf.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] If the user can grant that access, the application can retrieve the unique identifier for establishing the profile (identity) using the APIs.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] OpenID provides a cryptographic verification mechanism that prevents the attack below against users who misuse OAuth for authentication.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Note that the valet key does not describe the user in any way, it only provides limited access rights, to some house (which is not even necessarily the user's, they just had a key).
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Therefore if the key becomes compromised (the user is malicious and managed to steal the key to someone else's house), then the user can impersonate the house owner to the application who requested their authenticity.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] If the key is compromised by any point in the chain of trust, a malicious user may intercept it and use it to impersonate user X for any application relying on OAuth2 for pseudo authentication against the same OAuth authorization server.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Conversely, the notarized letter contains the user's signature, which can be checked by the requesting application against the user, so this attack is not viable.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The letter can use public-key cryptography to be authenticated.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] Published in February 2014 by the OpenID Foundation, OpenID Connect (OIDC) is the third generation of OpenID technology.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] It is an authentication layer on top of the OAuth 2.0 authorization framework.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] It allows computing clients to verify the identity of an end user based on the authentication performed by an authorization server, as well as to obtain the basic profile information about the end user in an interoperable and REST-like manner.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] In technical terms, OpenID Connect specifies a RESTful HTTP API, using JSON as a data format.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] OpenID Connect allows a range of parties, including web-based, mobile and JavaScript clients, to request and receive information about authenticated sessions and end users.
[src:azure-entra-id/openid-connect] The OpenID Connect specification is extensible, supporting optional features such as encryption of identity data, discovery of OpenID providers, and session management.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] ZTA is implemented by establishing identity verification, validating device compliance prior to granting access, and ensuring least privilege access to only explicitly-authorized resources.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] Most modern corporate networks consist of many interconnected zones, cloud services and infrastructure, connections to remote and mobile environments, and connections to non-conventional IT, such as IoT devices.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] The traditional approach by trusting users and devices within a notional "corporate perimeter" or via a VPN connection is commonly not sufficient in the complex environment of a corporate network.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] The zero trust architecture has been proposed for use in specific areas such as supply chains.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] The principles of zero trust can be applied to data access, and to the management of data.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] This brings about zero trust data security where every request to access the data needs to be authenticated dynamically and ensure least privileged access to resources.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] In order to determine if access can be granted, policies can be applied based on the attributes of the data, who the user is, and the type of environment using Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC).
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] This zero trust data security approach can protect access to the data.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] Several definitions of zero trust have been proposed since the term was first used in 1994.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] In April 1994, the term "zero trust" was coined by Stephen Paul Marsh in his doctoral thesis on computer security at the University of Stirling.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] Marsh's work studied trust as something finite that can be described mathematically, asserting that the concept of trust transcends human factors such as morality, ethics, lawfulness, justice, and judgement.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] The problems of the Smartie or M&M model of the network (the precursor description of de-perimeterisation) was described by a Sun Microsystems engineer in a Network World article in May 1994, who described firewalls' perimeter defence, as a hard shell around a soft centre, like a Cadbury Egg.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] In 2001 the first version of the OSSTMM (Open Source Security Testing Methodology Manual) was released and this had some focus on trust.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] Version 3 which came out around 2007 has a whole chapter on Trust which says "Trust is a Vulnerability" and talks about how to apply the OSSTMM 10 controls based on Trust levels.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] In 2018, the US National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) and National Cybersecurity Center of Excellence (NCCoE) published NIST SP 800-207 – zero trust architecture.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] The publication defines zero trust as a collection of concepts and ideas designed to reduce the uncertainty in enforcing accurate, per-request access decisions in information systems and services in the face of a network viewed as compromised.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] A Zero Trust Architecture (ZTA) is an enterprise's cyber security plan that utilizes zero trust concepts and encompasses component relationships, workflow planning, and access policies.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] Therefore, a zero trust enterprise is the network infrastructure (physical and virtual) and operational policies that are in place for an enterprise as a product of a zero trust architecture plan.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] In September 2025, the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI) Technical Committee CYBER (ETSI TC CYBER) published Technical Specification (TS) 104 102, which details the **ZT-Kipling methodology**.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] The ZT-Kipling methodology moves beyond the foundational principles of Zero Trust Architecture (ZTA) by defining a set of five mandatory, iterative steps.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] This methodology treats ZT as a continual and iterative process..
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] The core of the methodology’s systematic nature lies in its integration of the Kipling Criteria: what, why, when, where, who, and how.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] This entire process is repeated throughout the lifetime of a protected surface, which must be clearly defined in Step #1 of the methodology.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] TS 104 102 establishes the ZT-Kipling methodology as a systematic and cyclical governance framework for Zero Trust.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] In 2010 the term Zero Trust model was used by analyst John Kindervag of Forrester Research to denote stricter cybersecurity programs and access control within corporations.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] In 2003 the challenges of defining the perimeter to an organisation's IT systems was highlighted by the Jericho Forum, discussing the trend of what was then given the name "de-perimeterisation".
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] In response to Operation Aurora, a Chinese APT attack throughout 2009, Google started to implement a zero-trust architecture referred to as BeyondCorp an internal initiative to implement a zero trust security model that eliminated the need for a privileged VPN.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] Throughout the 2010s, zero trust architectures became more prevalent, driven in part by increased adoption of mobile and cloud services.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] In 2019 the United Kingdom National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) recommended that network architects consider a Zero Trust approach for new IT deployments, particularly where significant use of cloud services is planned.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] In the United States, Executive Order 14028 (May 2021) directed federal agencies to adopt zero trust architectures, and the Office of Management and Budget subsequently issued memorandum M-22-09 requiring agencies to meet specific zero trust security goals by the end of fiscal year 2024.
[src:azure-entra-id/zero-trust-security-model] In September 2025, the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI) Technical Committee CYBER (ETSI TC CYBER) published Technical Specification (TS) 104 102, which details the **ZT-Kipling methodology** to be used to achieve Zero Trust security posture.
